-- Japan, China, India, Indonesia, Philippines: Asian Bonds, Currency Preview
-- V. Ramakrishnan
-- 2010-07-12T22:15:09Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-12/japan-china-india-indonesia-philippines-asian-bonds-currency-preview.html

          
          
             The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in Asia’s local bonds and
currencies today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the
previous trading session unless stated otherwise.  
 Japan: The Ministry of Finance will sell 2.4 trillion yen
($27 billion) of five-year notes. The results will be announced
at 12:45 p.m. The Cabinet office will report Japan’s consumer
confidence for June at 2 p.m.  
 The yield on the 1.1 percent government bond due June 2020
was at 1.15 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co., the
nation’s largest interdealer debt broker.  
 The yen traded at 88.66 per dollar at 7:02 a.m. in Tokyo.  
 China: The central bank will sell 35 billion yuan ($5.2
billion) of one-year bills today. The government will sell 28
billion yuan of one-year bonds tomorrow.  
 The yield on the 2.53 percent note due in June 2015 was
2.57 percent. The yuan was at 6.7711 per dollar.  
 India: The wholesale price index rose 10.8 percent in June,
the most in three months, according to the median estimate in a
Bloomberg survey of economists before the release of data
tomorrow.  
 The yield on the 7.80 percent bond due May 2020 was 7.61
percent. The rupee was at 46.7775.  
 Indonesia: The government will sell five-year and 10-year
sukuks today.  
 The yield on the 11 percent bond due November 2020 was at
8.17 percent, according to Inter Dealer Market Association. The
rupiah was at 9,047 per dollar.  
 Thailand: The central bank will sell 32-, 91- and 182-day
bills today. The central bank will probably increase the
benchmark interest rate to 1.5 percent from the current 1.25
percent when policy makers meet tomorrow to review monetary
policy, according to the median estimate from economists
surveyed by Bloomberg.  
 The yield on the 5.375 percent debt due in December 2019
was 3.46 percent. The baht was at 32.36.  
 Malaysia: The government will sell 3 billion ringgit ($937
million) of five-year Islamic bonds tomorrow. The central bank
will sell 1 billion ringgit of 124-day Islamic notes and 1.5
billion ringgit each of 91-day notes and 210-day notes tomorrow.  
 The yield on the 3.835 percent debt maturing in August 2015
was 3.45 percent, according to Bursa Malaysia. The ringgit was
at 3.2040.  
 Philippines: Exports rose 25.5 percent in May from a year
earlier, the smallest gain this year, according to the median
forecast of economists surveyed by Bloomberg News before the
National Statistics Office publishes trade data today.  
 The yield on the 7.75 percent debt due February 2020 was
7.35 percent, according to Tradition Financial Services. The
peso was at 46.165.  
